post_text:
Join us for some high-tech fun @ JMS this summer! We are offering our Maker Camps under The Walpole Summer Program run through Walpole High School. It is designed to be challenging and fun, and our professional teaching staff is dedicated to providing a positive, safe learning experience for all of our summer program participants. Space is limited and the program is offered only to Walpole residents. Registration forms can be dropped off at Walpole High School main office through Thursday, July 9th. For more information and to access the registration form visit:
https://sites.google.com/walpole.k12.ma.us/makercamp2020/sessions

Tonight is the Community Forum regarding the "Rebel" name. This Forum will start at 6:00 p.m. on Zoom. We have approximately 75 community members speaking. We have received approximately 560 comments so far, and have also received a little under 200 emails.

You can watch this Forum live on Walpole Media TV (Comcast Channel 12 and Verizon Channel 29). You can also view it live on the Walpole Media TV YouTube here https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCQDKeXo5iHSejXrYDu-JB3w.

On Thursday June 11th, the Walpole School Committee became the 20th committee to join the growing statewide list of elected officials to call upon the State of Massachusetts to provide full reimbursement for whatever COVID-19 expenses are required to follow State mandates. In order to open schools safely in September, extensive planning must be underway now. "I think it is really important to get ahead of this now" stated Jennifer Geosits.

In the related conversation, School Committee chair Bill Buckley noted that the timing is excellent because the State budget is due to be released and debated in the coming weeks. Kari Denitzio was pleased to see the proactive nature as well, saying "I…

post_text:
Congratulations to the Walpole Speech and Debate Team for competing in one of the first virtual tournaments in the country! Students competed yesterday and today in this final state tournament. The Walpole Speech Team placed 9th in the rankings of schools! Only 10 schools were recognized and will receive team trophies. We had a smaller speech team compete since it was a holiday weekend, but the students proved that the size of our team did not matter. Bravo to our small group of students who rocked it this weekend:

Children's Literature Sophia Goodsell

Children's Literature Katerina Gebhardt

Children's Literature Stephen Bond

Declamation Erin Ledwith

Impromptu Regan Hegarty

Informative…

Walpole School Nutrition is feeling grateful in Walpole, Massachusetts.
March 21 at 5:23 PM · Walpole, MA ·

Wow! What a productive day.. We just finished distributing approximately 7,000 pounds of fresh, frozen and shelf stable food to 50 Walpole families. A huge thanks to the Walpole Food Pantry for donating food supplies and to our wonderful Walpole School Nutrition staff and their efforts in making this all happen!

post_text:
Dear Families,

As an abundance of caution and based on Governor Baker’s press conference, we have decided to postpone the Middle School Basketball Showdown scheduled for this Thursday, March 12, 2020.

District leadership continues to work closely with local and state authorities to monitor the situation and receives regular updates from the Department of Public Health, the Center for Disease Control, and Governor Baker’s Office. The information is fluid and ongoing. We are learning more by the day. Since this is an event that can easily be rescheduled to a time when more definitive information is available, we believe this is the best decision to make. Future decisions regarding other school events will be made on a case-by-case basis as we receive additional guidance.

We appreciate your understanding and continued support.
text:
Dear Families,

As an abundance of caution and based on Governor Baker’s press conference, we have decided to postpone the Middle School Basketball Showdown scheduled for this Thursday, March 12, 2020.

District leadership continues to work closely with local and state authorities to monitor the situation and receives regular updates from the Department of Public Health, the Center for Disease Control, and Governor Baker’s Office. The information is fluid and ongoing. We are learning more by the day. Since this is an event that can easily be rescheduled to a time when more definitive information is available, we believe this is the best decision to make. Future decisions regarding other school events will be made on a case-by-case basis as we receive additional guidance.

We appreciate your understanding and continued support.

post_text:
The Walpole High School Robotics Team, FRC 1153, had a very successful competition this past weekend at the Woodstock Academy in Woodstock CT. The students competed against a field of 39 other robotics teams from around New England for this year's challenge, which involves shooting 7" foam dodgeballs into a goal and then completing a pull up on a swinging bar. The team has worked tirelessly since January to develop and build this year's robot to complete the task and are proud to compete.

At the tournament, Walpole was one of the top scoring robots and was a total offensive powerhouse, having earned the top offensive power rating at the event. We were selected by the third seed and took…
text:
The Walpole High School Robotics Team, FRC 1153, had a very successful competition this past weekend at the Woodstock Academy in Woodstock CT. The students competed against a field of 39 other robotics teams from around New England for this year's challenge, which involves shooting 7" foam dodgeballs into a goal and then completing a pull up on a swinging bar. The team has worked tirelessly since January to develop and build this year's robot to complete the task and are proud to compete.

At the tournament, Walpole was one of the top scoring robots and was a total offensive powerhouse, having earned the top offensive power rating at the event. We were selected by the third seed and took…

post_text:
The team had a very busy February. Yesterday they competed at the Mardi Gras Tournament at Shrewsbury High School and placed 8th out of 46 schools! Congrats to the following finalists: Maggie W. placed 2nd in Impromptu and 6th in Informative Speaking. Lindsay N. placed 4th in speaker points for Lincoln-Douglas debate. Sydney N. placed 6th in Play Reading and Nolan G. placed 7th in Play Reading. Bravo!

Speech students competed at the Harvard Invitational on 2/15 and 2/16. This tournament is in the national circuit, so students competed with others from across the country! This was our second appearance at this prestigious tournament and was such a great experience.

Congratulations to debaters, Lindsay N. and Annika R. for competing at the NCFL Qualifers on 2/8. Congrats to Lindsay who placed 7th in Lincoln-Douglas Debate and was named first runner-up to compete at the NCFL Nationals in Chicago this May. If any qualifier from the Boston area is unable to attend, she will be invited to do so. Bravo!

post_text:
The Walpole High School Speech Team placed 6th out of 39 schools at yesterday’s Winter Festival at Newton-South High School- the team’s best placing at this tournament to date!

Congrats to the “Inside Out” multiple who placed first and features Stephen Bond, Gina Destito, Aislyn O’Connell, Emily Tomasetti, and Colin Wilber. Congratulations also to the following finalists: Gina Destito- 2nd in Radio Broadcasting, Katerina Gebhardt- 5th in Children’s Literature, Colin Wilber- 5th in Prose, Miles Ahmed- 6th in Radio, and Emily Tomasetti- 6th in Programmed Oral Interpretation. Bravo to Grace Buckley and Sydney Nossal for both earning honorable mentions in Play Reading. Well done!
